  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">This letter is a narrative of William Lloyd Garrison&apos;s tour through Pennsylvania to Ohio, &quot;with special reference to the Anniversaries of the Pennsylvania and Ohio Anti-Slavery Societies.&quot; He mentions the hospitality of James S. Gibbons and Abby H. Gibbons. He met Mrs. Sedgwick of Lenox and Mr. Henry Bleby, a missionary from Barbados. Friends assembled at J. Miller M&apos;Kim&apos;s house in Germantown, including James Mott and Lucretia Mott. A possible reason for the small attendance at the West Chester meeting was that a horticultural fair was just held there with a large attendance and the nearby farming population did not have more leisure time to attend the anti-slavery meeting. The testimony of the Pennsylvania Anti-Slavery Society was in favor of the dissolution of the Union. Garrison denies the anti-slavery character of the U.S. Constitution. He tells of Robert Collyer&apos;s advocacy of singing before unmusical Quakers. Garrison had a small meeting in Harrisburg. The West is in a state of depression.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Letter printed in The Liberator, Oct. 22, 1858; also in the National Anti-Slavery Standard, Oct. 30, 1858.</subfield>
  </datafield>
